subtasks.details:
1. Create component classes in a separate CSS file using @layer components
2. Implement iOS-style button classes with proper padding, border-radius, and transitions:
```
@layer components {
  .ios-button {
    @apply rounded-lg px-4 py-2 font-semibold transition-colors;
  }
  .ios-button-primary {
    @apply ios-button bg-ios-blue text-white dark:bg-ios-blue-dark;
  }
  /* Add more button variants */
}
```
3. Create form input styles matching iOS design
4. Implement card and container components with iOS-like shadows and borders
5. Add iOS-style toggle switches, segmented controls, and other UI elements
6. Create documentation with examples for each component

1. Create orientation-specific utility classes:
```
@layer utilities {
  .portrait-only { @apply block landscape:hidden; }
  .landscape-only { @apply hidden landscape:block; }
  /* Add more orientation utilities */
}
```
2. Implement touch-friendly sizing utilities:
```
@layer utilities {
  .touch-target-md { @apply min-h-[44px] min-w-[44px]; }
  .touch-target-lg { @apply min-h-[54px] min-w-[54px]; }
}
```
3. Create spacing utilities optimized for touch interfaces
4. Add utilities for handling safe areas and notches
5. Implement utilities for iPad-specific features (split view, slide over)
6. Create a responsive grid system optimized for iPad layouts

tasks.details:
1. Create TypeScript interfaces for equipment data models:
```typescript
interface Equipment {
  id: string;
  name: string;
  category: EquipmentCategory;
  shape: EquipmentShape;
  dimensions: EquipmentDimensions;
  specifications: EquipmentSpecs;
  touchTargetSize: { width: number; height: number };
  snapPoints: { x: number; y: number }[];
  clearanceZone: number;
  thumbnail: string;
}
```
2. Implement canvas state model:
```typescript
interface CanvasState {
  transform: Transform;
  selectedItems: Set<string>;
  activeGesture: GestureType | null;
  touchHistory: TouchEvent[];
  snapTargets: SnapTarget[];
  measurements: Measurement[];
}
```
3. Set up Context API providers for equipment and canvas state
4. Implement reducers for state management
5. Create custom hooks for accessing and updating state
6. Set up efficient state updates to maintain 60fps performance
